<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-271-934  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 271 934.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  May 15 1989 v8 n10 p83(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Weather project RFP on schedule. (request for proposals)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schwartz, Karen D.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Computer Sciences Corp. (contracts)Planning Research Corp. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    CSC.andO;Topic:     United States. National Weather ServiceInformation SystemsGovernment ContractsMeteorologyComputer Systems Integrators.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Weather Project RFP on ScheduleandM;National Weather Service officials said the Advanced Weather InteractiveProcessing System for the 1990s (AWIPS-90) is on schedule and they expect toissue a request for proposals by the end of the year.andM;Project manager Hank Schmidt said recently a contract would be awarded by theend of fiscal 1990 to develop the Presidential Priority System, which couldcost as much as $600 million by the time it is operational.andM;AWIPS-90 will connect weather reporting, analysis and observation systems inan effort to modernize the Weather Service's forecasting system.andM;Systems integrators Computer Sciences Corp. and Planning Research Corp. woncontracts in November worth $5.9 million and $5 million respectively todevelop competing designs for the system.andM;After the 21-month definition phase, one of the designs will be chosen fordevelopment.andM;The competition will be reopened for the development phase.andP;  The winningcontractor will develop, deploy and operate the AWIPS-90 network, completingthe modernization of the weather warning and forecasting system.andM;The system will be able to predict weather disasters such as tornadoes andflash floods more quickly.andM;Chuck Taylor, a spokesman for Planning Research Corp. of McLean, Va., saidAWIPS-90 will provide comprehensive analysis, display and computing tools forNational Weather Service forecasters to capitalize on the high-resolutioninformation produced by newly developed sensors.andM;Taylor said the modernization program also includes new weather radars,satellites and automated weather observing systems that are being acquiredseparately from the AWIPS-90 project.andO;</TEXT></DOC>